{{Infobox football biography |name = Pape Souaré |image = Pape Souaré (LOSC Lille).JPG |image_size = 150 |caption = Souaré playing for [[Lille OSC|Lille]] in 2014 |fullname = Pape N'Diaye Souaré<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|6|6|df=y}} |birth_place = Mbao, Senegal |height = 1.78 m<ref name = "NFT"/> |position = [[Defender (association football)|Left back]] |currentclub = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] |clubnumber = 27 |years1 = 2007–2008 |clubs1 = [[Diambars FC|Diambars]] |caps1 = |goals1 = |years2 = 2008–2012 |clubs2 = [[Lille OSC|Lille B]] |caps2 = 55 |goals2 = 7 |years3 = 2008–2015 |clubs3 = [[Lille OSC|Lille]] |caps3 = 53 |goals3 = 3 |years4 = 2012–2013 |clubs4 = → [[Stade Reims|Reims]] (loan) |caps4 = 23 |goals4 = 0 |years5 = 2015– |clubs5 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] |caps5 = 48 |goals5 = 0 |nationalyears1 = 2012 |nationalteam1 = [[Senegal national under-23 football team|Senegal Olympic]] |nationalcaps1 = 4 |nationalgoals1 = 0 |nationalyears2 = 2012– |nationalteam2 = [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] |nationalcaps2 = 22 |nationalgoals2 = 1 |club-update = 17:24, 11 August 2018 (UTC) |ntupdate = 18:09, 13 May 2018 (UTC) }} '''Pape N'Diaye Souaré''' ({{IPA-fr|pap swaʁe|lang}};<ref>{{cite web|title=Affaire Pape Ndiaye Souaré: Voici ce qu'en pense le sélectionneur, Aliou Cissé|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T500YSkJOEE|work=[[YouTube]]|date=16 September 2016|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref> born 6 June 1990) is a Senegalese professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|left back]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].
==Club career== Born in Mbao, [[Pikine Department]], Souaré spent his early career with [[Diambars FC|Diambars]], [[Lille OSC|Lille II]], [[Lille OSC|Lille]] and [[Stade Reims|Reims]].<ref name = "NFT">{{NFT player|pid=46802|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref name = "SW">{{soccerway|pape-souare/95905|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{lfpfr2|id=souare-pape-ndiaye|name=Pape Ndiaye Souare}}</ref>
He moved to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on a three-and-a half-year deal in January 2015 for an undisclosed fee,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31069468|title=Pape Souare: Crystal Palace sign Lille and Senegal defender|date=30 January 2015|accessdate=1 February 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> reported as £3.45 million.<ref name=debut>{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Dominic|title=Liverpool fight back to edge past Crystal Palace with Adam Lallana winner|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/14/crystal-palace-liverpool-fa-cup-match-report|accessdate=14 September 2017|work=The Observer|date=14 February 2015}}</ref> He made his Palace debut on 14 February in the fifth round of the [[FA Cup]], a 2–1 home loss to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], and was described by Dominic Fifield of ''[[The Observer]]'' as looking "rusty and susceptible".<ref name=debut/>
On 22 January 2016, it was announced that Souaré had signed a new three-and-a half-year contract with Palace.<ref>{{cite web|title=Souare Signs New Deal|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/2016/january/souare-signs-new-deal/|website=cpfc.co.uk|date=22 January 2016|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> He was sent off on 13 February at the end of a 2–1 loss to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] at [[Selhurst Park]], for fouling [[Valon Behrami]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lake|first1=Jefferson|title=Crystal Palace 1-2 Watford: Troy Deeney double downs Eagles|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/c-palace-vs-watford/341441|accessdate=14 September 2017|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 February 2016}}</ref>
After over a year out of football following a car crash, Souaré made his first appearance on 19 September 2017 in a 1–0 home win over [[Huddersfield Town]] in the third round of the [[EFL Cup]]. He was praised for his performance by manager [[Roy Hodgson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Crystal Palace 1-0 Huddersfield Town|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41235280|accessdate=20 September 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 September 2017}}</ref>
==International career== Souaré made his international debut for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] on 29 February 2012, in a goalless friendly draw against South Africa at the [[Moses Mabhida Stadium]] in [[Durban]].<ref name = "NFT"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fadjri|first1=Wal|title=Afrique du sud-Sénégal (0-0) : L'espoir est permis|url=http://www.seneweb.com/news/Sport/afrique-du-sud-senegal-0-0-l-rsquo-espoir-est-permis_n_60449.html|accessdate=14 September 2017|publisher=Seneweb|date=1 March 2012|language=French}}</ref> He later competed at the 2012 Summer Olympics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.losc.fr/actualites-foot-lille/jo-souare-decisif-avec-le-senegal|title=Souaré décisif avec le Sénégal|date=30 July 2012|language=French|publisher=Lille OSC}}</ref><ref>{{FIFA player|353769}}</ref> and was a squad member at the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30743603|title=2015 Africa Cup of Nations: Sadio Mane included in Senegal squad|date=9 January 2015|accessdate=1 February 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first international goal from a 20-yard free kick on 29 March 2016 as the ''Lions de Teranga'' won 2–1 away to [[Niger national football team|Niger]] in [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]].<ref>{{cite news|title=WATCH: Crystal Palace man scores awesome free-kick for his country Senegal|url=http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/watch-crystal-palace-man-scores-awesome-free-kick/story-29017847-detail/story.html|accessdate=14 September 2017|work=Croydon Advertiser|date=30 March 2016}}</ref> Following his car crash, he returned to the national team in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43318367|title=Souare back in Senegal squad after life-threatening car crash|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=9 March 2018|author=Momodou Bah|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>
He was not included in Senegal's squad for the 2018 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44161142|title=World Cup 2018: Pape Souare left out of Senegal squad|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=18 May 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>
==Personal life== On 11 September 2016, Souaré was airlifted to hospital after being involved in a road accident on the [[M4 motorway|M4]]. He sustained injuries to his thigh and jawbone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37337420|title=Pape Souare: Crystal Palace defender airlifted to hospital after M4 crash|date=12 September 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> It was thought that he would be out for 6 months,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37383412|title=Pape Souare: Crystal Palace defender could be out for six months|date=16 September 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> although he returned to training after 11 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40880691|title=Pape Souare: Crystal Palace defender back in training 11 months after car crash|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41088144|title=Pape Souare: Crystal Palace defender back in action|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>
